posts.name: Jared Van Horn
posts.cooked:
Our team made a few components from polycarbonate this year and the material was expensive . I was wondering if we’re somehow missing a cheaper alternative or if y’all are just biting the bullet for the large sheets you use. I see people using large pieces to protect electronics and it seems so pricy.

Edit: Follow up question, are y’all protecting your electronics with 1/8” or 1/4” polycarbonate?

posts.name: Max Morehead
posts.cooked: Shop for plexiglass sheets, acrylic, lexan polycarbonate, acrylic mirror, acrylic tubes, rods, styrene, and other plastics. Precut sheets or cut to size.

posts.name: Patrick
posts.cooked: How do you define expensive? You might be buying from a perfectly reasonable source.

EasyRuler stocks a large selection of plastic sheets including Polycarbonate, ABS, Acrylic and more with a focus on low prices and fast service. EasyRuler is ready to support you on your next plastics project.

posts.name: Sai 3035
posts.cooked: My team found a local polycarbonate fabrication company who gives us free scraps, which are actually pretty big sheets. Try asking local companies who use polycarbonate if they are willing to help your team out.

posts.name: Skye Leake
posts.cooked:
Sign companies in particular.

Make sure they know what you are up to so that acryic doesn’t sneak in.
Yes, local supply houses often have scrap available at a by-the-pound price, and they will usually give teams whatever they need from the scrap.

We have been getting ous for free.

Check with local companies who used it for shielding their offices and cubicles during the pandemic… We have found a few places that are dumping it now to get rid of it.

A large portion of our robot is built from Covid Lexan.

posts.name: Sai 3035
posts.cooked: My team learned that lesson the hard way, but thankfully we realized the problem during build season.

posts.name: Patrick
posts.cooked: That’s pretty much in line with what I’d expect. Certainly finding companies that have scraps to give away is great, we got a years worth of 1/4” from a sponsor who would have thrown it away otherwise. Finding the local suppliers and asking for charity discounts or sponsorship can be productive. The one other thing is to buy in bulk whenever possible. This summer we were buying about 25 sheets of 1/16” ABS for a special project and put a couple sheets of polycarb on the order for restocking the team. The polycarb was dramatically cheaper than when we buy a sheet or two at a time.
